From a2f7e1d3c8b946570123456789abcdef01234567 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Alexandre Cordeiro <nenisdeno@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 22 May 2026 10:30:00 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] Metal: per-stream MTL::CommandQueue for multi-model
 concurrency
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Today mlx::core::metal::Device holds a single shared MTL::CommandQueue
(`queue_`, device.cpp:269) that every MLX stream draws command buffers
from.  When multiple models are loaded in the same process and served
concurrently — as oMLX does with its multi-model mode — their streams
contend on the same queue.  Under sustained load (three 8B-class models
at mcr≥2 in one process) the Metal GPU watchdog fires
`kIOGPUCommandBufferCallbackErrorTimeout` errors because the command
scheduler cannot prioritise across models at the buffer level.

The per-process workaround (one oMLX process per model, each with its
own Metal context) eliminates errors but requires users to write
multi-service configurations and adds inter-process IPC overhead.

This commit refactors Device to maintain one MTL::CommandQueue per
active MLX stream, keyed by stream.index.  Each model on a distinct
stream gets an independent command queue, so the Metal driver can
schedule their workloads independently without cross-stream serialisation
at the queue level.

Design
======

Per-stream queue lifecycle
--------------------------
`Device::queue_for_stream(int stream_index)` is the single allocation
point.  It acquires `stream_queues_mtx_`, checks for an existing entry,
and allocates a fresh queue via `device_->newCommandQueue()` on first use.
`new_stream()` in eval.cpp calls it immediately before constructing the
CommandEncoder so the encoder always finds the entry pre-populated.
`CommandEncoder`'s constructor captures the returned SharedPtr by value,
giving the encoder shared ownership of the queue: in-flight command
buffers can complete even after the per-stream map entry is erased.

Safety cap
----------
Metal's per-process command-queue limit is typically ~256 (driver-
dependent; Apple documentation does not specify a minimum).  We cap
per-stream allocation at `kMaxStreamQueues = 64`, leaving ample headroom
for the Metal runtime, CoreML, and other in-process Metal clients.  Once
the cap is reached, `queue_for_stream` falls back to the device-global
`queue_` and emits a one-time `stderr` warning via `std::call_once`.
Capped streams see correct behaviour; they lose per-stream queue
isolation but do not crash or drop requests.

Teardown
--------
`Device::release_stream_queue(int)` erases a single entry.  It is called
from `clear_streams()` via `release_all_stream_queues()` after all
CommandEncoders have been destroyed.  Because encoders hold a SharedPtr,
the underlying MTL::CommandQueue is not deallocated until every in-flight
command buffer referencing it completes — Metal will keep the Objective-C
object alive regardless.

MTL::Event compatibility
------------------------
Metal events (`MTL::Event`, not `MTL::SharedEvent`) are device-scoped,
not queue-scoped.  A signal recorded on one queue's command buffer is
visible to wait encoders on any other queue attached to the same
`MTL::Device`.  Cross-stream event synchronisation in event.cpp is
therefore unaffected.  A comment is added at the relevant call sites to
document this invariant.

Composition with #2670
-----------------------
The exception-safety patch (#2670, commit 8c514a1a on the same branch)
keys stream error stashes by `stream.index` in `Scheduler`.  Per-stream
queues reinforce this design: a command-buffer failure on stream A's
queue stashes its error under stream A's index without polluting stream
B.  The generation-counter gap noted in #2670's "Known limitation" is
addressed by the companion M4 patch (Stream generation counter, planned).

Backward compatibility
-----------------------
Callers using the default single stream observe identical behaviour: they
get exactly one queue (stored in `stream_queues_` keyed by that stream's
index) rather than the device-global `queue_`.  The `queue_` member is
retained as the safety-cap fallback and for the Device destructor, which
releases it implicitly via SharedPtr.

Performance
-----------
`queue_for_stream` acquires a `std::mutex` only during the map lookup /
allocation.  The common no-allocation path (subsequent calls on an
existing stream) takes one mutex acquire + hash lookup + SharedPtr copy.
CommandEncoder construction is not on the hot eval path — it happens once
per stream at startup — so this is not a throughput concern.
Command-buffer creation (`stream_queue_->commandBuffer()`) is identical
to before: a single Objective-C message on the queue.

Risks and open questions
------------------------
1. The driver cap of ~256 queues per process is empirical; it may be
   lower on A-series chips or under memory pressure.  The 64 cap is
   conservative; we have not benchmarked queue allocation under the
   full 64 per-stream limit on M4 Pro or M4 base.  Needs reviewer with
   Metal background and hardware access to validate.
2. The thermal / scheduling behaviour of 64 concurrent queues under
   sustained multi-stream load is untested.  Multi-queue submission could
   theoretically interact poorly with Metal's internal scheduler on
   constrained GPUs.
3. This patch does NOT validate end-to-end on Metal hardware —
   specifically the multi-model oMLX scenario that motivated the change.
   Integration testing against the per-process baseline (Fleet L,
   mac-mini) is required before merge.

Tests
-----
`tests/test_metal_per_stream_queue.cpp` (new file, compiled only with
`MLX_BUILD_METAL`) covers:
  1. A fresh stream yields a non-null queue; repeated calls return the
     same queue (idempotency).
  2. Two distinct streams have distinct (non-aliasing) queues.
  3. `release_stream_queue` removes the map entry; subsequent allocation
     succeeds (non-null result).
  4. The safety-cap fallback: once `kMaxStreamQueues` entries exist, a
     further call returns a non-null queue that differs from per-stream
     entries (i.e., the device-global fallback).

The existing test suite (`MLX_BUILD_METAL=ON`) must continue to pass.
